value.value: This gene is involved in both transcriptional repression and cell differentiation.

Human ZNF281 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 1q32.1 and is approximately 4 kb in length. This allele, which encodes zinc finger protein 281, plays a role in the regulation of cell differentiation and the modulation of gene transcription.
Zinc finger protein 281 (895 aa, ~97 kDa) is encoded by the human ZNF281 gene. This protein is involved in the modulation of both gene expression and cell differentiation.
This gene is involved in the regulation of apoptosis.

Human BCL2L12 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19q13.3 and is approximately 9 kb in length. This allele, which encodes Bcl-2-like protein 12, plays a role in the negative regulation of apoptosis. Aberrant expression of the gene is associated with various cancers.
Bcl-2-like protein 12 (334 aa, ~37 kDa) is encoded by the human BCL2L12 gene. This protein is involved in the inhibition of apoptosis.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of glucose and fatty acid metabolism.

Human PDK4 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 7q21.3 and is approximately 13 kb in length. This allele, which encodes [pyruvate dehydrogenase [lipoamide]] kinase isozyme 4, mitochondrial protein, is involved in the modulation of pyruvate dehydrogenase activity.

[Pyruvate dehydrogenase [lipoamide]] kinase isozyme 4, mitochondrial (411 aa, ~46 kDa) is encoded by the human PDK4 gene. This protein plays a role in the inhibition of pyruvate dehydrogenase activity.
An undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma that occurs during childhood.

label.value: Childhood Undifferentiated High Grade Pleomorphic Sarcoma of Bone

value.value: An undifferentiated high grade pleomorphic sarcoma that arises from the bone and occurs during childhood.
Infection of the peritoneum related to a peritoneal dialysis catheter.
A non-infectious inflammation of the peritoneum.
A bulge in a weakened vessel wall segment of an arteriovenous fistula.
Narrowing of the lumen of an arteriovenous fistula.

An antineoplastic vaccine directed against a peptide found in the epidermal growth factor receptor class III variant (EGFRvIII), a constitutively activated mutant of the wild-type tyrosine kinase. This protein variant is present in a substantial proportion of malignant gliomas and other human cancers.
Partial or complete occlusion of the lumen within an arteriovenous fistula by a thrombus.
Any compound or agent that acts to prevent the activity of P-glycoprotein.
A bulge in a weakened wall segment of an arteriovenous graft.
A gliosarcoma that arises from the brain stem and occurs during childhood.
A mixed glioma that arises from the brain stem and occurs during childhood.
A form of intensity-modulated radiation therapy that uses narrow pencil beams of protons to deliver radiation to a precise target while sparing surrounding tissues.
Narrowing of the lumen of an arteriovenous graft.
Partial or complete occlusion of the lumen of an arteriovenous graft by a thrombus.
Blockage of a dialysis catheter by a thrombus or other substance.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 22 in somatic cells.

A rare, autosomal recessive inherited disorder of long-chain fatty-acid oxidation caused by mutations in the CPT2 gene. The disease includes three main types: a lethal neonatal form, a severe infantile hepatocardiomuscular form, and a myopathic form.

An autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutations in the GALK1 gene. The disorder is characterized by an accumulation of galactose and galactitol secondary to the decreased conversion of galactose to galactose-1-phosphate by galactokinase. Its major clinical symptom is the development of cataracts during the first weeks or months of life.

A rare autosomal dominant inherited disorder of connective tissue caused by mutations in either the TGFBR1 or TGFBR2 gene. Like Loeys-Dietz syndrome type I the disease is characterized by enlargement of the aorta and other arteries, and arterial tortuosity, but skeletal signs are typically less severe or absent in type 2. Skin abnormalities, such as velvety skin are often present in type 2.

A rare autosomal dominant form of diabetes mellitus affecting young people with a positive family history. MODY is a form of monogenic diabetes, resulting from mutations in a single gene. The most common forms are HNF1alpha-MODY (MODY3) and GCK-MODY (MODY2), due to mutations in the HNF1A and GCK genes, respectively.

An autosomal recessive inherited disorder caused by mutations in the XPC gene. This disease is characterized by increased sensitivity to sunlight with the development of carcinomas at an early age and is caused by a defect in nucleotide excision repair.

An autosomal recessive genetic disorder caused by mutations in the DDB2 gene. This disease exhibits the mildest degree of sun sensitivity of all xeroderma pigmentosum complementation groups, although individuals are at high risk for skin cancer.
Thrombus formation within an apparatus that carries blood outside of the body, such as pheresis, dialysis or extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO).
An oligodendroglioma that arises from the brain and occurs during childhood.

value.value: A supratentorial embryonal tumor, not otherwise specified that occurs in childhood.
A neuroblastoma that arises from the central nervous system and occurs during childhood.
Leakage of blood into the dialysate during hemodialysis due to apparatus malfunction.
A germ cell tumor that occurs during adulthood.
A germ cell tumor that arises within the cranium and occurs during adulthood.
A non-Hodgkin lymphoma that arises from the central nervous system.
Inadequate development of an arteriovenous fistula within three months of creation.

A complication occurring during hemodialysis that is thought to be due to a rapid decrease in blood urea nitrogen, and is characterized by an increase in intracranial pressure resulting in nausea, headache, vomiting, restlessness, and/or a decreased level of consciousness.

Hodgkin lymphoma that occurs during pregnancy.
Non-Hodgkin lymphoma that occurs during pregnancy.
